<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: OSCAR WATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More on the Case of the Disappointed Jurist Desperately Seeking Oscar Tickets: 
"People's Court" Judge Joseph Wapner, who last week was in search of a ticket 
to the Academy Awards, has decided to just stay home and watch. He had wanted 
to attend the festivities because of Dustin Hoffman's repeated references to 
him in the much-nominated film "Rain Man," and a Warner Bros. rep even went so 
far as to try and get him booked onto the show. That plea was over-ruled by 
Oscar show producer Allan Carr. Now, it turns out, Wapner will be taping his 
own show on Wednesday, then will spend the evening in front of the TV like 
millions of others to watch the Oscar outcome. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
