METRO DIGEST: LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
TRASH RECYCLING CENTER OPENED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mayor Tom Bradley and other Los Angeles city officials broke ground Monday for 
a downtown trash recycling center and transfer station intended to reduce truck 
traffic on freeways and the amount of refuse dumped at landfills. 
</P>
<P>
The facility at 2201 E. Washington St. will accept trash from private and 
public trash haulers so their trucks will not have to travel 40 miles to a 
landfill, said Tony Harris, spokesman for the city Department of Public Works. 
</P>
<P>
With the controversial Lopez Canyon facility near Lake View Terrace the only 
city-owned landfill still in operation, city officials have increasingly looked 
to recycling as a way to reduce the amount of waste going into dumps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
