<P>
NWA Inc., the parent company of Northwest Airlines, said today that an investor 
group holding 4% of its stock is exploring the possibility of a leveraged 
buyout of the company. 
</P>
<P>
The news sent NWA's stock sharply higher. In morning trading on the New York 
Stock Exchange the stock soared $8 to $68.625 a share, a gain of 13.2%. 
</P>
<P>
NWA has been rumored as a takeover target, partly because of its holdings of 
prime real estate parcels in Tokyo, the world's most valuable market for land. 
</P>
<P>
NWA did not identify the group, but signaled that it would oppose a buyout, 
saying its board has determined the company's interests are best served by 
staying independent. In a leveraged buyout a company is taken private in a 
transaction financed primarily by debt. 
